{
  "text": "\u03b3-rays can be produced in both hadronic interactions (with subsequent pion decay) and from energetic electrons that inverse Compton scatter off background photon fields. An ambiguity therefore exists in the responsible radiating particle population when detecting \u03b3-rays from SNRs, and determining the hadronic or leptonic nature of the accelerating mechanism remains a key issue. Since neutrino detectors have not yet proven to be sensitive enough to detect neutrinos from astrophysical sources, no direct indicator of either process currently exists. However, disentangling the radiation processes can be facilitated by studying SNR \u03b3-ray spectra extending well beyond 10 TeV, where inverse-Compton spectra tend to cut off due to strong radiative energy losses of the parent electron populations, or by studying SNRs interacting with dense molecular clouds where the target material in the cloud could boost the \u03b3-ray component from a hadronic mechanism. For the reasons outlined above, the SNR G318.2+0.1 may be a prime target for studying VHE \u03b3-ray emission and the radiation mechanism that generates the emission. G318.2+0.1 is a large diameter (40\u2032\u2032\u00d735\u2032\u2032) shell-type SNR discovered in the Molonglo Observatory Synthesis Telescope (MOST) survey [CITATION_1] and is characterized by two non-thermal filaments in the Northwest and Southeast which form two sections of a shell, and a central region of thermal emission which corresponds to a HII region.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "55434221"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "55434221": {
      "title": "The MOST supernova remnant catalogue (MSC)",
      "abstract": "A catalogue of supernova remnants in the southern Galaxy within the area 245 l 355,jbj< 1:5 has been produced from observations made at 0.843 GHz with a resolution of 43 00 using the Molonglo Observatory Synthesis Telescope (MOST). The catalogue, presented here, provides greyscale images and contour maps of known and newly-discovered remnants. The increased resolution and sensitivity of these observations has resulted in better statistics for southern remnants."
    }
  }
}